<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Marshall's-Racism     09-18 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marshall's-Racism,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Store Fined, Agrees To Anti-Racism Training</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marshall's, a department store company,
has agreed to pay a $17,500 fine to settle a lawsuit filed by a
customer over a racial incident at one of its stores, the company
said.
   The company said it also has agreed to conduct an anti-racism
training program for its employees. The company announced the
settlement at a news conference in Oakland on Friday.
   Cynthia Sterling, 25, who is black, sued Marshall's after she
tried to exchange an $80 comforter at the Marshall's store in
Newark, about 15 miles south of Oakland. She was shown a memo
written by a store supervisor instructing clerks not to allow
blacks to return bed linens ``for any reason.''
   The supervisor was later fired and the store issued an apology.
   Sterling and the store also agreed to a monetary settlement, but
both sides agreed not to disclose details. The fine was a penalty
assessed by the judge who approved the settlement of the civil
lawsuit.
   In another agreement between Marshall's and the state Department
of Fair Employment and Housing, the store agreed to develop
anti-racism guidelines for employees and distribute them throughout
the chain.
   Marshall's also agreed to develop an internal system to allow
customers to complain if they believe they have been discriminated
against, and to notify the local branch of the National Association
for Advancement of Colored People of progress with the agreement.
</TEXT>
