<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 0153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Noriega     09-18 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega: U.S. Has Invited Me To Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has sent two messages to
Panamanian military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega in recent days
inviting him to resume bilateral talks that collapsed in May, the
general said in an interview.
   Noriega said he sees the alleged overtures by the U.S.
government as a ``positive step'' and added that his regime is
ready to start ``serious, scientific and realistic'' negotiations
immediately, The Miami Herald reported from Panama in its Sunday
edition.
   U.S. officials confirmed there were meetings with ``members of
the ruling coalition'' in the last few days, but added these were
part of ``regular meetings with a cross-section of Panamanian
political leaders.'' They denied these were proposals for new
negotiations.
   Noriega said he is ready to meet face-to-face with ousted
president Eric Delvalle ``without preconditions,'' if that helps
solve Panama's crisis.
   Previously, Noriega said he would never sit down with Delvalle,
who unsuccessfully tried to fire him as commander of Panama's
Defense Forces early this year.
   Noriega had generally shunned the press since he was indicted
Feb. 4 in Miami and in Tampa for drug smuggling and his country
exploded into political crisis.
   The Herald interview Thursday was at the main office of the
General Torrijos military base in Rio Hato, about 68 miles
northwest of Panama City.
   The U.S. government in May offered to lift two drug indictments
against Noriega, if he would step down. But subsequently,
presidential candidates George Bush and Michael Dukakis both said
they oppose any deal that would result in dismissal of the
indictments.
   Referring to the U.S. dispatches, Noriega said, ``We have
received a message from the U.S. Embassy transmitted to us through
(Panama's) commerce minister Mario Rognoni, with suggestions or
open doors to continue the talks that had been suspended.''
   John Maisto, the U.S. Embassy's deputy chief of mission,
delivered the message last Wednesday to Rognoni, Noriega said.
   An embassy official said ``written talking points'' were
delivered describing U.S. positions on Panama, but said they were
summaries of on-the-record U.S. policy. The State Department has
set out guidelines that no further negotiations with Noriega are
expected.
   The Reagan administration has said it still recognizes Delvalle,
who is in hiding in Panama, as the head of state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
