<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Gilbert-Tourists     09-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert-Tourists,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Fetches U.S. Tourists Stranded In Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost 200 tourists expressed their relief and
thanks over being home when they landed here Saturday night after
enduring Hurricane Gilbert in Cancun, Mexico.
   Damage in the Mexican resort was extensive, said passengers upon
arrival at Miami International Airport at 8:53 p.m. EDT.
   ``Cancun doesn't exist anymore,'' said Ana Maria Cardoso, who
weathered the hurricane in a hotel. ``We were lucky. Our hotel is a
very old, well-built building.
   ``Unfortunately, those poverty stricken people are really
suffering. They're going to have to start all over again.''
   ``Everybody's glad to be home,'' said Angela Harvey, 23, of
Atlanta.
   The first thing the tourists requested was fresh water, said an
Eastern Airlines crew member.
   Eastern does not normally fly to Cancun, but arranged for an
L-1011 jet with room enough for 316 passengers to pick up the
stranded tourists after the U.S. State Department appealed for
help, said the airlines' chief spokesman, Robin Matell.
   Hundreds of Americans were scattered in shelters in Cancun,
passengers said, but only 196 made it to the airport in time to
take the flight.
   Eastern delayed takeoff for almost two hours and sent members of
the plane's ground crew into town in hopes of picking up more
passengers, but many tourists never got the word, the passengers
said.
   The airline encouraged Miami area hotels to let the tourists
stay overnight free of charge, Matell said.
   ``We're trying to keep their costs to a minimum,'' he said.
   Miami accommodations would be a welcome change compared to the
shelters they stayed in during the hurricane, said Medina
Sutherland, 24, of Chattanooga, Tenn.
   ``They put eight of us in a room with two beds, no power, no
lights, no food and no plumbing for two days,'' she said. ``We had
never met before. Now we're best friends.''
   Gilbert was a fierce storm when it rammed the Yucatan Peninsula
Wednesday, killing 29 people and badly damaging the popular resort
towns of Cancun and Cozumel.
   But after making landfall again Friday in northern Mexico,
Gilbert quickly lost power. It was downgraded to a tropical
depression Saturday.
</TEXT>
