<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Haiti-Profiles     09-18 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Profiles,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profiles Of Figures In Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti-Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief profiles of some of the figures in Saturday's
coup that deposed Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in Haiti:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Namphy _ Took over after President Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to
exile in France on Feb. 7, 1986. Returned to power after ousting
the 4-month-old civilian government of President Leslie Manigat on
June 19. Namphy previously ruled for two years following Duvalier's
flight to France. Namphy said he removed Manigat and his government
because the president illegally blocked the transfers of several
officers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Brig. Gen. Prosper Avril _ Also adjutant general of the
military, was believed named new head of state, according to Frantz
Lubin, the government's director of information. Many observers
believe Avril, who had been a military adviser to Duvalier, was a
key figure in the coup in June. Avril was head of the presidential
guard when Manigat tried in June to relegate him to an
administrative post before the coup. Avril was an adviser to the
military-led junta until anti-government demonstrations forced him
to resign that post in early 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Col. Jean-Claude Paul _ Commander of Dessalines Barracks and
considered second-most powerful figure in the military after
Namphy, was believed named the new commander-in-chief of the army,
according to Lubin. Behind Namphy, Paul was considered the most
powerful figure in the military regime. In March, Paul was indicted
by a federal grand jury in Miami for allegedly conspiring to import
cocaine into the United States. Paul denied any involvement. The
700-man Dessalines Barracks, the 7,000-member military's largest
unit, lies adjacent to the presidential palace. In June, Namphy
reassigned Paul to an administrative position, but Paul, with
backing from then-President Leslie Manigat, refused. Namphy then
ousted Manigat.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Franck Romain _ Mayor of Port-au-Prince, the capital, until
Duvalier's ouster. Returned to that office in army-run elections in
January and remained after Namphy ousted Manigat. In commenting on
a massacre Sept. 11 in which 13 parishioners were killed at a
church led by the Rev. Jean-Bertrand Aristide, an outspoken critic
of the military government, Romain said Aristide was ``justly
punished'' by the incident. A former colonel in ex-dictator
Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier's presidential guard and former
chief of police under Jean-Claude Duvalier, Romain denied city hall
had been involved in the killings.
</TEXT>
