<HEAD>Tunisian Diplomat Expelled for Unpaid Parking Tickets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to DELETE extraneous wording in lead,
Foreign Office confirming article; pickup 3rd graf pvs, `The
article ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tunisian diplomat has been expelled for failing
to pay hundreds of dollars in parking fines, the Foreign Office
said Saturday.
   The office confirmed a published report in Sunday's editions of
The Mail, in which Foreign Office Minister Timothy Eggar wrote that
administrative attache Sadok Kassous was ordered to leave about
three weeks ago as part of a crackdown on envoys who break the law.
   The article did not give an exact figure.
   The report of Kassous' departure follows the expulsion within
the past week of three diplomats _ Cuba's ambassador, a Cuban
attache and a Vietnamese envoy _in connection with firearms
violations.
   In 1984 diplomats in London failed to pay about 100,000 parking
tickets, he said.
   The newspaper, in a separate article on the expulsion, quoted
Tunisian economic attache Hatem Bergaoui as saying Kassous refused
to pay the tickets because his embassy was allocated three parking
spaces for six diplomats.
   A Foreign Office official said he did not know when Kassous left
the country.
   Cuba's ambassador and commercial attache were expelled Tuesday
after the attache opened fire in a London street and wounded a man.
Cuba said he fired at a CIA operative trying to get him to defect.
   Their expulsion came within days of a Vietnamese diplomat being
ordered out for brandishing a gun at demonstrators outside his
embassy.
</TEXT>
