<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protesters Arrested In New Jersey, California</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 1 graf to UPDATE with 450 arrested. Picks up 2nd
graf, `The arrests ...' Subs 4 grafs for 9th graf to UPDATE with
San Francisco arrest total at 200. Picks up 11th graf, ```We're
just ...' EDITS to trim and conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   About 450 anti-abortion activists were arrested during
demonstrations Saturday outside clinics where abortions are
performed in New Jersey and California, police said.
   The arrests were the latest resulting from Operation Rescue, a
New York-based organization that has spawned anti-abortion protests
around the nation in recent months.
   Police in Shrewsbury, N.J., arrested about 250 chanting and
singing protesters for blocking entrances to a Planned Parenthood
clinic.
   ``We picked Planned Parenthood because they are the McDonald's
franchise of the abortion industry,'' said Chris Slattery, a
spokesman for Bi-state Operation Rescue Network, which organized
the demonstration in Shrewsbury, about 45 miles southeast of Newark.
   The Planned Parenthood in Shrewsbury is the only one of eight in
New Jersey that performs abortions as well as provide family
planning counseling, said Phyllis Kinsler, executive director of
Planned Parenthood of Monmouth County.
   She said the 15 or so women who had appointments for abortions
for Saturday were warned of the demonstration, but none rescheduled
their appointments.
   ``Ironically, what has happened is that these people scared away
walk-ins who may have wanted birth-control devices or
information,'' she said. ``At the same time, the people who wanted
the abortions were there. They showed up.''
   The demonstrators were taken to the Shrewsbury Fire Department,
where they were arraigned on charges of trespassing and violating a
1984 court injunction that prohibits protests at the clinic.
   In San Francisco, about 200 people were arrested Saturday when
they surrounded the Pregnancy Consultation Center, police said.
   Police Chief Frank Jordan said the arrest procedure was very
lengthy because demonstrators were ``lifted up and carried away,
which is very time consuming.''
   ``We were trying to be as diplomatic as possible,'' said Sgt.
Jerry Senkir. ``But it's obvious these people want to be arrested.''
   In New Jersey, police estimated 250 anti-abortion protesters and
50 counterprotesters demonstrated at the center, which performs
abortions twice a week.
   ``We're just trying to prevent abortions,'' said Liz Brouth, a
spokeswoman for Operation Rescue, which claims 1,000 members in
California.
   Brouth said 250 members and supporters surrounded the facility
starting at 7 a.m. However, police later cleared a path to the back
entrance for employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
