<1ST_LINE>u a AM-YellowstoneFires 2ndLd-Writethru a0669 09-18 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone Fires, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0669,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Firefighters Rejoice In Forecast Of Up To 6 Inches Of
Snow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 15th graf pvs `Elsewhere, officials...' to
UPDATE with release of firefighters and weather in Montana. Picks
up 16th graf pvs, `High humidity ...' Subs last graf to UPDATE with
increased acreage of Oregon fires. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A forecast for up to 6
inches of snow gave firefighters prospects Saturday of reinforcing
battle lines against fires that have burned for nearly three months.
   ``This forecast is music to our ears,'' said Ken Dittmer, one of
Yellowstone's area commanders.
   But high winds preceded the storm, with more than 40 mph gusts
in some areas. Firefighters fought a fire that threatened Roosevelt
Lodge because of the winds.
   ``I hope this thing decides to take a nap soon,'' said Capt. Ron
Goetzinger, who heads a team of firefighters from Brainerd, Minn.
``The snow should take care of it. We sure hope so.''
   The storm, forecast to swing into Yellowstone sometime Saturday
night, was expected to leave much of its moisture on the northern
sections of the country's first national park, Dittmer said.
   Fires burning in northern Yellowstone, including the
335,300-acre North Fork blaze, have been the most active in recent
days and got the least moisture from a front that passed through
the park a week ago, according to the commander. That previous rain
represented about the first significant moisture in the park since
spring.
   ``It couldn't come to a better place,'' he said.
   The North Fork fire is the one that burned buildings in the
tourist complex at Old Faithful geyser, and threatened West
Yellowstone, Mont., and park headquarters at Mammoth Hot Springs.
   It and other fires have blackened almost half of the
2.2-million-acre park.
   Despite progress toward containment of the flames with fire
lines, park officials declined even to venture when the blazes
could be called controlled. Officials would say only that they
predict the North Fork, half contained Saturday, may be fully
contained sometime the middle of next month.
   The National Weather Service said showers would change to snow
during the night with accumulations of 4 to 6 inches possible by
Sunday morning. Daytime temperatures were expected to remain in the
40s and 50s through Wednesday, falling below freezing at night.
   ``It's time to break out the sweaters,'' commented park
spokeswoman Judy Jennings.
   She said the fires did not grow Friday despite gusty winds that
whipped up flames after several days of calm.
   Other major fires in the park included the 411,500-acre
Clover-Mist fire in northeastern Yellowstone, 75 percent contained
Saturday, and the 225,500-acre Huck-Mink fire in southern
Yellowstone and the Bridger-Teton National Forest, declared fully
contained.
   Elsewhere, officials gave a day off to some firefighters in
Glacier National Park, where a 35,000-acre fire has resisted
efforts to douse it, and crews were released from another wildfire
as steady rain and snow pelted much of western and central Montana
Saturday.
   The weather bureau issued a winter storm warning for today in
western and central Montana, predicting up to a half-foot of snow
in the foothills and a foot of snow in the mountains.
   High humidity and temperatures in the 40s helped firefighters in
Idaho to keep most fires within the boundaries of the Frank
Church-River of No Return, Gospel Hump and Selway-Bitterroot
wilderness areas. Still active fires had charred nearly 200,000
acres.
   ``The only thing consistently in our favor is winter is
coming,'' said Mary Zabinski, spokeswoman for the Nez Perce
National Forest in central Idaho.
   In Oregon, a $5,000 reward has been offered for information
leading to the conviction of the person responsible for starting a
forest fire that had burned 8,200 acres of the Willamette National
Forest by Saturday. Investigators believe it was started by a
careless hunter with a cigarette.
</TEXT>
