<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Marcos     09-18 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Marcos,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Says Possible Indictment Based on Hearsay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos said Saturday that reported
efforts by U.S. officials to indict him for fraud ``are mere
repetitions of charges pending in the Philippines.''
   The Los Angeles Times reported Saturday that federal officials
have overcome major legal obstacles in their case against the
deposed Philippines leader and likely would ask a federal grand
jury to indict him.
   ``I will not try to guess what the motivation is (behind the
possible federal indictment), but as I have said in the past
several times and so have my lawyers _ we can prove the charges are
false and we have evidence to do so,'' Marcos responded through a
spokesman.
   Marcos said 35 cases are filed in a Philippines court involving
billions of dollars allegedly misappropriated during and after his
20-year rule.
   ``And so, why is there an effort to file a similar case in the
United States which are mere repetitions (sic) of charges pending
in the Philippines?'' Marcos asked.
   The indictment is expected to deal only with alleged of
wrongdoing after Marcos left the Philippines during a
civilian-military revolt that swept Corazon Aquino to power in
February 1986, the newspaper reported.
   According to the report, the investigation focuses on
allegations that Marcos and his wife, Imelda, conspired with others
to violate U.S. District Court injunctions by secretly transferring
ownership of hundreds of millions of dollars in stolen art and
Manhattan real estate bought with Philippine government funds.
</TEXT>
