<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>RANGOON: street protests.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Saw Maung became Burma's fourth leader since the July 23
resignation of Ne Win, who had ruled the country since he staged a
military coup 26 years ago.
   Saw Maung, the 59-year-old armed forces commander, also became
defense minister in July.
   Maung Maung, who took power Aug. 19, had offered to end Burma's
one-party rule hold general elections under a multiparty system as
early as late October.
   But increasingly restive demonstrators said Maung Maung's
authoritarian Burma Socialist Program Party party could not be
trusted. Protesters have demanded the formation of an interim
government to conduct the polling _ something the authorities had
given no indication they would concede.
</TEXT>
