<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoudoirPhotos     09-18 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boudoir Photos,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boudoir Photo: An Intimate Gift For the Man Who Has Everything</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some women are finding that a boudoir photo makes
the perfect gift for the boyfriend or husband who has everything.
   At Design Studio Chicago, Nancy Binder, a 39-year-old insurance
executive, posed for a photographer while sprawled on a black
leather sofa with an emptied bottle of Dom Perignon champagne and a
black mink coat on the floor.
   She was clad in high heels, sheer nylon stockings, garter belt
and a black silk teddy with the straps hanging off her shoulders.
   ``I was engaged to a man who literally had everything, so for
his birthday I got him this,'' she said of the photos. ``It's
completely opposite of my corporate image. Doing it was a fantasy
for me, something very personal.
   ``I would recommend that any woman do it. Men, too.''
   In the Chicago area, more than 30 studios offer boudoir
photography _ soft, sexy portraits to be given to boyfriends or
husbands.
   A 1986 industry survey indicated that boudoir photography was
the fastest growing segment of the business.
   ``It's stylized photography, a very intimate portrait of a
woman,'' said photographer Daniel Byrnes, who took the shots of Ms.
Binder.
   It also is definitely not a cheap gift.
   Byrnes, who has done this sort of work for four years, charges
$250 or more for a session. Other Chicago photographers quote
prices ranging from $150 to $500.
   But the photographers can give customers their money's worth.
   Mattresses or a strategically draped sheet can be used to hide
fat. After the shots are taken, retouching can eliminate stretch
marks, facial puffiness and dark circles under the eyes.
   ``We know how to make a woman look good,'' Byrnes said.
   Steve Schnur, a photographer at Furia Studios in Chicago, said
customers sometimes ask him to duplicate a pin-up picture or even a
shot from the Sports Illustrated swimsuit calendar.
   ``Others just say, `Make me look sexy, make me look 10 years
younger,''' Schnur said.
   Men have also started posing for their ladies and there is a
trend toward portraits of couples.
   Paula Ray, 32, a Chicago actress and model, said she had her
picture taken embracing her boyfriend in softly erotic poses.
   ``Posing with my boyfriend made it more personal than posing
alone,'' she said. ``The pictures captured the way we are when
we're together.''
   But sometimes a boudoir photo is not the perfect gift.
   Sherri Northrup, a Chicago writer-publicist, said she paid $800
for a series of color shots two years ago as a St. Valentine's Day
present for her husband.
   Ms. Northrup, now divorced, said her husband hardly reacted.
   ``He just kind of blew the whole thing off, like it was no big
deal,'' she said. ``I should have got divorced right then and
there.''
</TEXT>
