<1ST_LINE>r p AM-HawaiiPrimary     09-18 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hawaii Primary,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Newcomer Wins Hawaii's Democratic Congressional Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Bitterman, a former Voice of America
director seeking her first elective office, beat two other
Democrats in Hawaii's state primary and will face first-term
Republican Rep. Patricia Saiki in November.
   Former Democratic City Councilwoman Marilyn Bornhorst won the
right to face Republican Honolulu Mayor Frank Fasi after defeating
three other former council members and a community activist in
Saturday's election.
   Voters also chose nominees for 100 federal, state and local
offices.
   Bitterman, 44, received 51,942 votes, while Honolulu City
Councilman Leigh-Wai Doo had 35,579 and former teachers union
executive John Radcliffe trailed with 15,258.
   Saiki, 58, was unopposed in the GOP primary for the urban
Honolulu district.
   U.S. Sen. Spark Matsunaga, 71, had an easy time with his
little-known Democratic opponent, Honolulu writer Bob Zimmerman.
Matsunaga gathered 180,853 votes, or 82 percent, to Zimmerman's
27,360, or 12 percent, and faces Libertarian candidate Ken
Schooland in the general election.
   Six-term U.S. Rep. Daniel Akaka, whose district includes
outlying areas of Oahu and the Neighbor Islands, was unopposed in
the Democratic primary. His only competition in November will come
from Libertarian Lloyd Mallan.
   Fasi, 68, received 36,608 votes, almost 90 percent, to easily
defeat two relatively unknown candidates in the Republican primary.
Gordon Nelson finished second with 1,167 votes and Charles Hirayasu
had 1,035 votes.
   Bornhorst, 61, received 57,097 votes to defeat former Council
members Patsy Mink, Randall Iwase and Dennis O'Connor, and activist
Jerry Souza. Mink got 48,771, Iwase and O'Connor trailed with
22,906 and 21,585 votes respectively and Souza had 3,469.
   Bornhorst, Iwase and O'Connor were required by law to give up
their City Council seats to run for mayor. Mink resigned her
council seat two years ago when she mounted an unsuccessful
campaign for governor.
   There was little bad blood in the two major Democratic primary
races. In fact, the three Democrats who sought to unseat Saiki
became known as ``The Three Amigos'' because of their reluctance to
criticize each other and their general agreement on the issues.
   The Democrats stressed their professional backgrounds and
government experience in their appeal to voters.
   Bornhorst, a 13-year City Council veteran, is the front-runner
in the Honolulu mayor's race, according to a recent Honolulu
Advertiser-Channel 2 News poll. Although she leads Fasi in the poll
for the general election, Fasi was narrowing the gap and many
voters were still undecided.
   Fasi served three terms as a Democratic mayor before losing in
the 1980 primary. He came back as a Republican and won again in
1984.
</TEXT>
