<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Spending Bjt   09-18 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Spending, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Omnibus Spending Bill Is Possible, Despite Last Winter's Pledges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember President Reagan's nationally
televised pledge last January to veto future catchall spending
bills like the $600 billion behemoth Congress sent him last year,
and the promises by scores of lawmakers from both parties not to do
it again?
   Guess what may be about to happen.
   As the Oct. 1 start of the 1989 fiscal year approaches,
increasing numbers of senators and representatives, and their
aides, concede that an omnibus spending bill looms as a real
possibility.
   It wouldn't be as large as last year's. After all, two of the 13
individual appropriations bills that finance the government have
already been signed into law, and four others have been sent to
Reagan for his signature.
   But with the presidential campaign influencing much of what
happens in Washington these days, and with the hopper stuffed with
legislation Congress wants to pass before leaving town next month,
a catchall spending bill may well be the result.
   ``I don't see any way out of that scenario right now,'' Sen. Ted
Stevens of Alaska, a ranking Republican on the Appropriations
Committee, said recently.
   Everyone agrees that come Oct. 1, a short-term omnibus bill is
virtually unavoidable, providing financing for a week or two for
all agencies for which money has not yet been provided for the new
fiscal year.
   But if spending legislation is not finished by the time Congress
adjourns in mid-October, lawmakers would likely either pass another
omnibus bill to tide the government over until Congress returns in
January, or send the president a package of all remaining
appropriations bills and dare him to veto it.
   The engine that would drive such a measure would be defense.
Reagan has already vetoed a Pentagon budget bill containing arms
control language and cuts in the ``Star Wars'' missile defense
system, a rejection that was interpreted as an effort to make
defense an issue in the presidential campaign.
   Many lawmakers still support those provisions. If Congress and
the White House cannot work out a compromise _ or if they send a
measure to Reagan and he vetoes it again _ a catchall bill would be
born, consisting of the defense spending bill and other unsigned
measures.
   ``There could be a situation, if we run into a problem on the
defense appropriations bill, in which there would have to be a
continuing resolution in the final analysis,'' Senate Majority
Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., using the congressional term for
catchall spending legislation, warned his colleagues two weeks ago.
   Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., a member of both the House Budget and
Appropriations Committees, said Reagan ``thinks he's created an
issue ... They may figure they can rekindle it by vetoing an
appropriations bill.''
   Some Democrats say one scenario would be to send the president a
package of bills containing the defense legislation and other
spending measures, thus making it painful for the president to
exercise a veto and eliminating another opportunity for Republicans
to raise the defense issue.
   ``He threw us a curve by vetoing that defense bill,'' said Rep.
Les AuCoin, D-Ore., a member of the defense appropriations
subcommittee. ``No one down Pennsylvania Avenue should be surprised
if we use every strategy in the book to launch that curve out of
the ballpark.''
   However, Congress' Democratic leadership has vowed repeatedly
this year to try to send Reagan 13 separate spending bills by the
Oct. 1 start of the fiscal year.
   Few lawmakers have forgotten the president's State of the Union
address of Jan. 25, when he hoisted thick stacks of spending and
tax bills that were months overdue and said, ``Congress shouldn't
send another one of these. And if you do, I will not sign it.''
   Reagan accused lawmakers of trying to force him to accept
excessive spending, while Congress blamed the president for being
so intractable for so long that lawmakers had no other choice.
Nonetheless, dozens of senators and representatives signed letters
chastising the use of omnibus spending bills, a belief that many
retain.
   ``They make Congress as an institution look bad,'' says Rep.
Timothy Penny, D-Minn., a perennial opponent of omnibus spending
measures.
   For his part, the president is standing firm on his words of
last January.
   ``I hope Congress will watch my lips here: I want 13 separate
bills,'' he said Friday.
   Whatever happens, that Congress has gotten even this far is a
remarkable feat for an institution that is a notorious budget
laggard.
   The House passed all 13 appropriations bills this year before
July 1, the first time that had happened since 1960. Congress
hasn't approved all 13 appropriations bills separately since fiscal
1977.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
