<HEAD>Helicopter Crashes In Sierra Leone, 6 Saved, 2 Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A helicopter carrying eight people
crashed into the sea Sunday after taking off in a rainstorm, and
navy sources said six people were rescued and two were missing.
   The Polish-built helicopter was scheduled to fly from Freetown
International Airport on Lungi Island to downtown Freetown, a
15-mile journey, said naval sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   A Sierra Leonean navy unit rescued the pilot and five passengers
and was searching for the two passengers who were missing, the
sources said.
   The passengers boarded the Provincial Air Service helicopter
after arriving in this northwestern African nation on a flight from
London.
   The rescued passengers are Lebanese nationals and the pilot is a
Polish national. The nationalities of the missing people were not
known.
