<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Radon     09-18 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radon,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radon's Shadow Remains Over Town That Put It on The Map</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOYERTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly four years after radon from his
house caused Stanley Watras to set off radiation detectors at the
Limerick nuclear power plant, he wonders daily about his family's
health.
   ``There's a fine line between making yourself sick by worrying
and having a genuine concern and doing the best you can,'' said
Watras, 37, a technical adviser at the plant.
   Radon levels in Watras' home of 800 times the concentration
deemed hazardous first alerted environmental officials and
residents of southeastern Pennsylvania to the danger of indoor
radon concentration. Last week, the head of the Environmental
Protection Agency said the problem is more widespread than
previously believed and urged that every home in the country be
tested.
   Radon is a radioactive gas produced by the natural decaying of
uranium found in all soil and rock and usually dissipated
harmlessly into the atmosphere. It poses a health threat when it
seeps through the ground and collects in homes.
   The colorless, odorless gas could be responsible for 20,000 of
the nation's 130,000 annual lung cancer deaths, the EPA estimates.
It kills by leaving its own radioactive decay products in the lung,
irradiating the organs for a lifetime.
   Environmental officials first believed radon to be concentrated
along a geological formation known as the Reading Prong, a narrow
area of high-uranium soil stretching from Reading, Pa., across
northern New Jersey into New York state.
   But a recent EPA survey in seven states and Indian land found
health-threatening levels of radon in 29 percent of 11,000 homes
tested.
   The EPA has set 4 picocuries of radon per liter of air as a
guideline for determining when long-term exposure poses a health
threat. A picocurie is a measure of radiation. Exposure to 15
picocuries of radon for a lifetime is equivalent to smoking a pack
of cigarettes a day, the EPA says.
   A reading taken in the living room of Watras' modest,
split-level house in December 1984 was 3,200 picocuries, the
highest ever recorded at a private home. Watras, his wife and two
young children were evacuated soon afterward.
   Tim Hartman, administrator of the state Radon Monitoring Program
set up several miles away in late 1985, said the Watrases' house
was built inches above uranium-laden granite.
   ``He just had an ungodly concentration of radon spewing into his
home,'' Hartman said.
   Watras and his family returned to the house in August 1985 after
a $32,600 research project dramatically reduced the radon level.
Watras and his wife have since had a third child.
   ``At the beginning, we were saying, `Why us?' We were looking at
the children saying, `What did we do to you?''' Watras recalled in
an interview at his home last week.
   Watras now believes God put his family in the home for a purpose.
   ``What we've got to do from now on is try to help other
people,'' he said, calling his efforts to bring attention to radon
``a crusade.''
   Some of the other residents in his suburban Berks County
neighborhood, nicknamed Radon Hills, agree with him and have
organized to push for legislation protecting homes from the toxic
gas. Others believe the threat is overblown.
   Kay Jones, who lives down the street from Watras, is president
of Pennsylvanians Against Radon, a group with about 150 members.
   Ms. Jones believes national building codes should include radon
guidelines, wants public service advertisements that warn people
about the danger of radon and supports a law that would force a
family to leave a home when radon levels reach a certain point.
   Unless the government acts, people will forget about radon as
media interest wanes, she said.
   ``Right now, everything you pick up, it's radon, radon, radon,
but in two or three days it's going to die out,'' Ms. Jones said.
   Dennis Hess, another neighbor, is one of those skeptical about
the radon threat.
   ``I don't think I'm walking into a gas chamber when I walk into
my home. I'd like to think something else will get me before the
radon,'' said Hess, a 34-year-old machinist at a chemical plant.
   Hess hasn't measured the radon level in his home, and he said
environmental officials haven't been able to convince him that the
problem can't be alleviated by opening a few windows.
   No records exist of the number of people who have had their
homes refitted in Pennsylvania to reduce the amount of radon in the
air. Hartman estimated the number was in the thousands, most of
them along the Reading Prong, where 60 percent of the homes tested
had levels above 4 picocuries.
   Even when houses have been fixed, health worries remain.
   ``The fear never goes away,'' said Ms. Jones, whose family spent
five years in a home that recorded a radon level of 450 picocuries
before being fitted with a ventilation system. ``We're living in
the unknown.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
