<DOCNO> AP880918-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GoldenFleece     09-18 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Golden Fleece,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire Gives Golden Fleece for Agency's Disney World Trip</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source; DelliBovi in
3rd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. William Proxmire awarded his latest
Golden Fleece award to the Urban Mass Transit Administration for
sending government officials to Disney World to learn how to
motivate employees, his office said Sunday.
   The September installment of the Wisconsin Democrat's monthly
award for wasteful federal spending was for a four-day seminar that
cost the agency $68,160.
   ``UMTA apparently hopes that by sending mass transit officials
from around the country to Disney World, Minnie Mouse, Goofy, Snow
White and the Seven Dwarfs will help them find out how to make
transit employees whistle while they work,'' Proxmire said in a
written statement.
   Attending the Sept. 6-9 session in Orlando, Fla., were six top
UMTA officials _ including its chief, Alfred A. DelliBovi _ and 47
local mass transit officials from around the country. The officials
paid their own travel expenses, but UMTA picked up the tab for the
$110 per night hotel rooms and the $795 program fee for each.
   ``This is an idea Dopey would have loved, but it's likely to
make taxpayers feel like Grumpy,'' the senator said.
   UMTA spokesman James Bynum said Friday that agency officials are
worried that only 2.8 per cent of all travel by Americans is made
on mass transit, the lowest percentage since the government began
making the estimate 20 years ago.
   Bynum said the trip served two purposes: To allow officials to
learn how Disney World officials motivate their workers and to
examine the amusement park's huge transportation system. Both would
provide helpful lessons for agencies trying to boost ridership, he
said.
   ``It was a perfectly legitimate effort to convince public
transit authorities that there are ways to attract new riders,''
Bynum said. ``Government would do well to draw on the experience of
successful private companies.''
   The seminar, called ``The Disney Approach to People
Management,'' was also attended by executives from private
industry, Bynum said.
   Proxmire, however, said he doubted that allowing government
officials to ``frolic in the Magic Kingdom with federal dollars''
would prove helpful.
   ``Instead of a trip to Disney World, maybe mass transit
officials can improve employee morale by wearing Mickey Mouse ears
around bus yards,'' he said. ``It would cost far less, and it would
probably accomplish as much as this wasteful trip.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
