<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CongressRdp 820   09-18 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress Rdp, 820,Bjt</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Considers Raising Minimum Wage This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When their party regained control of the
Senate two years ago, liberal Democrats placed at the top of their
agenda raising a minimum wage that President Reagan claimed had
``caused more misery and unemployment than anything since the Great
Depression.''
   With only seven weeks remaining until voters pick Reagan's
successor, his former running mate and GOP-designated heir, George
Bush, may have waffled just enough on the issue in the past two
weeks for Democrats to push through the first increase in the $3.35
an hour wage base in eight years.
   Labor Department figures indicate that a raise to $4.55 by 1991
as proposed by Senate Democrats would directly benefit some 15
million workers now paid less than that amount.
   Bush said again last Friday that he could support a modest
increase _ less than the $1.20 an hour over three years that
Democrats have agreed upon _ but only if it is coupled with a lower
``training wage.''
   Key Senate Republicans such as Pete Domenici of New Mexico
predicted that Bush's slight shift to muted support for a wage
increase will cause many GOP lawmakers to reconsider their
opposition with or without the training wage.
   The training wage is the latest Republican euphemism for a
subminimum wage, a Reagan idea that went nowhere when the
administration proposed it year after year during his first term
but that succeeded in taking the steam out of a push for an minimum
wage increase.
   To quote Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.,
paraphrasing Indiana University basketball coach Bobby Knight:
``There is nothing that a good defense cannot beat a better
offense. In other words, a good offense wins.''
   But with the Senate expected to complete action on the minimum
wage this week followed by House action the next week, Bush, Quayle
and congressional Republicans are stuck on defense.
   The latest Gallup Poll on the issue on June 19 showed 76 percent
public support for raising the minimum wage by 50 percent to $5.05
over the next four years, with only 28 percent opposition. Even
Republicans who were polled favored the raise by 67 percent to 30
percent.
   The raise to $5.05 over four years is the House Democratic
version of Massachusetts Democrat Edward M. Kennedy's increase to
$4.55 over three years in the Senate. House leaders already have
indicated they will abandon their proposal in favor of the Senate
version.
   As a Republican counter, Quayle _ who has led the Senate
opposition to a minimum wage increase the past 7{ years _ in July
offered a 65-cent raise over two years to $4 an hour, coupled with
a lower training wage.
   Republicans, however, declined to push for a vote on Quayle's
amendment in the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee then,
saying they preferred to wage the battle on the Senate floor.
   While Bush and the Republican campaign have declined to specify
what they want in a minimum wage package, Sen. Rudy Boschwitz,
R-Minn., said he will introduce Quayle's $4 minimum wage as an
amendment this week.
   And Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, has a pending amendment on the
Senate floor to establish a ``training'' wage that would pay any
new hire 80 percent of the minimum wage for the first 90 days he or
she is on an employer's payroll.
   But because Democrats control the Senate, Hatch's proposal may
never get a direct vote. Kennedy offered a substitute that would
slightly expand coverage of an 85 percent subminimum wage _
currently $2.85 an hour _ for full-time students that is now in the
law. About 100,000 students are paid that subminimum.
   If Kennedy's parliamentary gambit works and a majority supports
his subminimum proposal, Republicans may be precluded from ever
getting a yea-or-nea vote on their training wage.
   Hatch expressed doubts last week that he would prevail. But with
many lawmakers in both parties taking last Friday off to campaign
for re-election, he succeeded in delaying any votes until at least
Tuesday when presumably all will have returned.
   Kennedy, meanwhile, welcomed Bush's vague support for any kind
of minimum wage increase.
   ``I only wish that he had spoken up sooner,'' Kennedy said,
returning to his ``Where was George?'' theme at the Democratic
National Convention. ``I must say that his silence has been
deafening during debate on this bill.''
   Meanwhile, the Senate is scheduled to vote Monday evening on a
U.S.-Canada trade agreement that would phase out all tariffs
between the two countries over 10 years.
   The House in August approved the agreement negotiated by the
Reagan administration. But its anticipated passage by the Senate
and then signature by the president does not mean that it will go
into effect soon.
   The bill authorizes Reagan to implement the agreement next Jan.
1. But it has been approved by only one of Canada's two legislative
bodies.
   If Canadian Prime Minister Brain Mulroney, as expected, calls
new parliamentary elections in the next two or three weeks,
legislation there implementing the accord could die in Canada's
Senate. A new parliament would then have to start from scratch on
enacting the agreement.
</TEXT>
