<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0778 09-18 0912</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Home for a Day, One Week Before Big Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 4th graf, Meanwhile; Mitchell is not whip</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   One week before their high-stakes debate, George Bush and
Michael Dukakis took Sunday off before heading into a week of
reduced campaigning amid intense preparation for their first
televised confrontation before a national audience.
   Bush, in brief remarks to reporters in Washington, said he'd
``done all the homework'' for the debate but still planned to work
later in the week on preparing for it.
   Dukakis, who was out of the public eye in Boston, also planned
to ease off on his recently full-speed campaign travels later in
the week to concentrate on getting ready for the debate.
   Meanwhile, Sen. George Mitchell of Maine, a top-ranking Senate
Democrat, defended the party's nominee against recent attacks by
Bush and other Republicans.
   In particular, Mitchell took the Republicans to task for their
criticism of Dukakis' veto of Massachusetts legislation that would
have required teachers to lead classes in the Pledge of Allegiance.
   ``There is no greater phony issue that's been raised in this
campaign,'' Mitchell said on ABC's ``This Week With David
Brinkley.'' He said, ``In America, the pledge means something
because we say it freely. ... We are not forced to do so.''
   Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois, a co-chairwoman of the national
Bush campaign, criticized Mitchell for linking the issue to loyalty
oaths in Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union. She said such comments
show why the issue ``is working against Michael Dukakis and
should.''
   As for next Sunday's debate in Winston-Salem, N.C., the first of
two presidential confrontations before the Nov. 8 election, Bush
said, ``I think I've done the homework. It's like a ballgame,
getting up for it, mentally up and physically up.''
   The vice president, speaking with reporters after attending
church services, said he planned to work this week on preparing for
the debate ``but not today. It's Sunday, a day off. I'm going to
get a little exercise and count my blessings.''
   Monday morning campaign appearances in the Philadelphia area, a
Tuesday visit to a flag manufacturing company in New Jersey and a
joint appearance with President Reagan on Thursday in Texas were
Bush's only scheduled trips for the week.
   The vice president said he didn't expect to visit areas in
southern Texas damaged by Hurricane Gilbert. He said of the
hurricane, ``It's a sad thing. Fortunately, it was less strong when
it hit. But still there is a lot of heartache.''
   Dukakis, who spent most of last week on the road, giving major
speeches on foreign and military policy, also planned to
concentrate on getting ready for the debate during the coming week.
   Still, the Massachusetts governor, who returned home only
Saturday night, was to embark on a campaign trip to Texas on Monday.
   The vice presidential running mates, Democrat Lloyd Bentsen and
Republican Dan Quayle, also were off the campaign trail on Sunday.
   Bush, who attended services at St. John's Church, an Episcopal
church on Lafayette Square across from the White House, with his
wife, Barbara, answered several questions afterward.
   Asked about the military coup in Haiti, he said, ``It's too
early to say what happened.'' But he added, ``We want democracy for
Haiti, for the whole of the Caribbean and for the whole of Central
America.''
   He said such a trend appears to be occurring in Latin America
``with some visible exceptions.''
   Asked if he favored a resumption of talks with Panama's leader
Gen. Manuel Noriega, Bush would say only, ``We want democracy in
Panama'' as well as through the rest of the region.
   On another television talk program, Lee M. Thomas, administrator
of the Environmental Protection Agency, said Bush had asked him on
two occasions if more could be done to fight acid rain than was
called for by Reagan administration policies.
   Thomas, on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said, ``At least twice,
individually with me, he pulled me aside on the issue of acid rain
and asked if we could do more _ and frankly at that point in time,
I didn't think we should _ than where we were going on that
problem.'' He did not say when the inquiries occurred.
   In the campaign, Bush has said, ``I am an environmentalist,''
and has said there were many occasions when he argued within the
councils of the administration for more environmental protection.
He says he will back a program to reduce emissions of one major raw
material for acid rain, sulfur dioxide from smokestacks, by
unspecified millions of tons.
   Thomas has supported the administration's position that not
enough is known about the effects of acid rain to justify a major
emissions reduction program, and that more research is needed.
   Dukakis on Saturday said he would elevate EPA to the status of a
Cabinet department.
   Meanwhile, a new poll suggested Bush has overtaken Dukakis in
Ohio, a key state in which Dukakis had once led by 10 percentage
points.
   The University of Akron poll, commissioned by The (Akron) Beacon
Journal, WKYC-TV in Cleveland and WCMH-TV in Columbus, indicated
that 43 percent of the registered voters checked in the survey
favored Bush to 39 percent for Dukakis and 18 percent undecided.
Bush's lead was within the poll's margin of potential sampling
error _ four points in either direction.
   The poll was conducted by telephone among 667 registered voters
between Sept. 6 and last Thursday.
</TEXT>
