<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Chrysler     09-18 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Chrysler,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Automobile Heir, Museum Benefactor Dies In Norfolk At Age 79</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter P. Chrysler Jr., an art collector and
museum benefactor whose father founded Chrysler Corp., has died of
cancer at the age of 79.
   Chrysler, who died Saturday at Sentara Norfolk General Hospital,
divided his time between New York City and Norfolk, hometown of his
wife, Jean. He had devoted much of his life to building a
multimillion-dollar art collection that is housed at the Chrysler
Museum in Norfolk.
   ``The Chrysler Museum and the commonwealth have lost a great
friend and patron,'' museum director David Steadman said Sunday.
``Mr. Chrysler was a rare collector whose encyclopedic interests
distinguished him from others.''
   He purchased his first work of art, a Renoir, for $350 at age
14. But the painting, a landscape with an inch-high nude, drew the
disapproval of a teacher at the Hotchkiss School in Connecticut,
where Chrysler was a student.
   ``The corridor master thought it unbecoming for young men to
have such paintings,'' Chrysler said in a 1980 interview. ``So he
busted it over his knee and threw it in the trash can.''
   Later at Dartmouth University, Chrysler founded an arts magazine
with another student, senior Nelson Rockefeller.
   He went against trends, buying paintings by as-yet unrecognized
artists. In the 1970s, he sold a Picasso for $1.6 million that he
had bought 30 years earlier for $450.
   The first Chrysler Museum was in Provincetown, Mass. In 1970,
Chrysler agreed to move the collection to Norfolk after the city
offered to rename its museum for him and add a wing, as well as
naming a concert hall at Scope for him.
   Since then, the collection has grown in size, value and
reputation. It was called one of the top 20 in the country by the
Wall Street Journal and has an 8,000-piece glass collection, one of
the finest in the world.
   In addition to his art collecting, in 1934 Chrysler founded the
Air-Temp division of Chrysler, which developed the first air
conditioning system on wheels.
   Chrysler is survived by several nieces and nephews.
   A memorial service will be held Tuesday at the Church of the
Good Shepherd in Norfolk. Burial will be Wednesday in the family
plot in Tarrytown, N.Y.
</TEXT>
