<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentShot     09-18 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Shot,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crack-Addicted Parolee Charged in Pratt Student's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack-addicted, paroled killer has been
charged with slaying a 24-year-old art student because she refused
to give him her pocketbook, police said. The robbery netted $27.
   Judith Ann Wrappe, a native of Little Rock, Ark., and a
first-year graduate student at Pratt Institute, had been in New
York just a week when she was shot to death early Wednesday, police
said.
   Saturday night, police arrested Frank DeChirico, 37, of
Brooklyn, and charged him with Miss Wrappe's murder, said Deputy
Inspector Charles Prestia.
   Detectives from the Brooklyn North homicide squad and
investigators from the state parole office were able to identify
DeChirico from information obtained from witnesses and street
sources, he said.
   DeChirico, arrested nine times since 1966 on charges including
robbery, drug possession, grand larceny and burglary, had been out
on parole since December 1986 after serving 13{ years for
manslaughter charge in a 1973 killing, police said.
   ``He is a local crack addict who spends a lot of time on the
street,'' Prestia said at a news conference. ``We believe the
robbery was for the purpose of getting money for drugs.''
   ``We were looking for him, spotted him and he was taken into
custody without incident,'' the police official said.
   DeChirico was charged with second-degree murder, robbery,
criminal possession of a dangerous weapon and criminal possession
of stolen property. Prestia said DeChirico was charged with the
weapons count even though the gun used in the killing has not been
found.
   The deputy inspector said DeChirico stole $27. Miss Wrappe's
purse contained $1 and other personal effects when found by police
the day after the killing.
   Miss Wrappe's mother, Sue Wrape, said her daughter, a 1987
graduate of Notre Dame, had moved to New York ``to pursue her
dream'' of becoming a successful artist.
   She was confronted by a robber as she was returning to her
Brooklyn dormitory from her waitress job about 1 a.m. Wednesday.
When she resisted, she was killed by a single bullet to the chest.
   ``It makes me feel better that he's off the street,'' Mrs.
Wrape, whose family spells the surname the traditional way, said in
a telephone interview from Little Rock.
   ``I'm sure the police and the judicial system will take care of
it from here, and we can count on justice being done.''
   Prestia said DeChirico made no statements after his arrest.
   A disheveled DeChirico, who was unable or unwilling to stand on
his own as he was taken from the precinct house by police, simply
said ``no'' when reporters asked him if he were guilty.
   His arrest came hours after hundreds mourned Miss Wrappe at a
requiem Mass in her hometown, and Bishop Andrew J. McDonald
remembered her as a gifted artist who ``marched to a different
drummer'' and ``was not afraid to be different.''
   She is survived by her parents, four brothers and a sister.
</TEXT>
