<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HolocaustMemorial     09-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holocaust Memorial,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holocaust Survivors Help Dedicate Monument To Six Million Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALATINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 people chanted a memorial prayer
for the dead Sunday as six Holocaust survivors lit candles during
dedication ceremonies for a monument called the ``Tower of
Remembrance.''
   The 80-foot granite tower _ topped by a 10-foot-high ``Eternal
Flame'' covered with gold leaf _ was erected at Sholom Memorial
Park in this Chicago suburb to honor the 6 million Jews killed in
World War II.
   ``It means a great deal for me because I went through the
Holocaust myself,'' said survivor Pola Mishell, of Skokie, who lit
her candle in memory of the Jews from her native Lithuania who died
in the war.
   Mrs. Mishell, a Hebrew teacher now in her early 60s, said she
has been active in recording and speaking about her recollections
as a teen-ager during the Holocaust.
   After the Nazis emptied the Jewish ghetto in her small
Lithuanian town, she spent 1944-45 in the Stutthof concentration
camp near the present-day Polish city of Gdansk.
   ``I feel this monument is very important because after we are
all gone something will remain to remind people that such horrible
things all happened,'' she said.
   The dedication ceremony took place during the Jewish High Holy
Days _ on the Sunday between Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New Year,
and Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement _ when the cemetery holds its
annual Kever Avot, or Resting Place of our Fathers, memorial
service at which families remember loved ones buried there, said
Jules Mellow, a spokesman for the cemetery.
</TEXT>
