<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricaneAftermath     09-18 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Aftermath,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Returning Cozumel Vacationers Recalls Gilbert's Fury</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane-Flooding, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who returned from a hurricane-marred
vacation Sunday said hundreds of frantic tourists were still
stranded on the battered resort isle of Cozumel, Mexico, when they
left.
   ``The airport was a madhouse,'' said Fletcher Walls of Johnson
City, Tenn. ``I'm very concerned about the conditions on Cozumel
and about the people down there.''
   He said the island's drinking water was exhausted and food and
medical supplies were running low.
   ``Cozumel is in bad shape,'' he said. ``There is no electricity
on the island and no communications with the mainland. We felt cut
off from the rest of the world after Wednesday, the day the storm
hit the island.''
   Walls said he and his wife, Sandra, were lucky to have been able
to get aboard an unscheduled charter flight that left Cozumel late
Saturday night. They arrived in Atlanta a few hours later, after a
refueling stop at New Orleans.
   ``As of Saturday, only Continental Airlines was flying into
Cozumel,'' he said. ``There were fistfights at the airport the day
before. The people there are scared. They need help.''
   He said the eye of Hurricane Gilbert passed just six miles north
of Cozumel, a small island located 11 miles off of Mexico's
Caribbean coast, 30 miles south of Cancun.
   ``People were evacuated from Cancun, but I don't know of anyone
who was able to get off of Cozumel before the storm hit,'' he said.
``There wasn't any way to leave the island once the wind picked up
and the seas got rough.''
   Authorities on Cozumel didn't seemed overly worried about the
storm until Tuesday, Walls said.
   ``Everyone seemed to think it would turn northward and miss
us,'' he said. ``But the hotel management called a meeting Tuesday
night and told the guests that Gilbert had hit Jamiaca and
apparently would reach Cozumel the next day, unless it changed
course. By then, the wind had already started to pick up.
   ``We were given some emergency supplies _ candles, drinking
water and food _ and were told to lock ourselves in the bathroom
and prop our mattress up against the bathroom door, if the storm
came our way.''
   He said he and his wife had a second-floor room and were able to
ride out the storm in that fashion.
   ``The air pressure got intense, but the sound of the wind was
the worst part,'' Walls said. ``The noise was terrific. A gust of
wind blew out our big picture window shortly after the hurricane
hit. Later, the skylight popped out and a light fixture came loose
and began banging and clanging; it sounded like the roof was coming
off.
   ``The storm hit us Wednesday morning about 6:30 a.m. and lasted
until 2 p.m. It was interesting but I wouldn't want to do it again.
We were told some of those wind gusts exceeded 200 miles per hour.''
</TEXT>
