<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SynagogueArson     09-18 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Synagogue Arson,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congregation Mourns As Two Youths Are Held in Synagogue Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orthodox Jews on Sunday mourned the loss of six
sacred scrolls that police said were set afire in a synagogue by
two neighborhood boys.
   About 5,000 people, including Mayor Edward I. Koch, turned out
for the service near Congregation Sharai Torah in the heavily
Jewish Flatbush section of the borough of Brooklyn.
   Two boys, ages 12 and 15, were arrested and accused of setting
fire to the torah scrolls and spray-painting 15 swastikas on the
walls of the synagogue. The fire damaged the interior of the
building and its contents.
   The incident occurred early Saturday, the Sabbath between Rosh
Hashana and Yom Kippur, the two holiest days on the Jewish calender.
   ``You couldn't do a worse crime to the Jewish people,'' said
City Councilman Noach Dear, who described the mood of the community
as one of anger, hurt and puzzlement.
   The two boys were charged Sunday as juvenile delinquents with
arson, burglary and criminal mischief, said Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell,
a police spokesman. They were released to the custody of their
parents.
   Neither boy is Jewish, according to another police spokesman,
Officer Hugh Barry. Barry said both youths lived near the synagogue.
   Dear said the replacement cost of the scrolls could be as high
as $50,000 each. Torahs, containing the first five books of the Old
Testament, are considered the holiest objects in Judaism. It takes
one person about one year to produce one, inscribing it by hand
under exacting religious guidelines.
   Rabbi Hillel David held a funeral service Sunday for the torahs
in accordance with Jewish law, with burial in a cemetery.
   ``He's in mourning,'' Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said of
David, who founded the congregation in 1965. ``It's as if he lost a
child.''
   The congregation is temporarily using a Jewish high school for
prayer.
   Koch said Sunday he was relieved that the suspects were
juveniles and ``not members of some organized adult organization.''
   ``The fact that they're juveniles puts a somewhat different cast
on the vicious action of arson and bias that took place,'' Koch
said. ``They have to be punished. They (also) have to be carefully
taught to respect and tolerate and even to love.''
   Others, however, found it chilling that the suspects were so
young. ``This scares everybody,'' Dear said.
   The incident came against a backdrop of a rising number of
anti-Semitic incidents nationwide, according to the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith.
   ``I have never heard of any desecration in the United States in
recent years where that number of torahs was destroyed,'' said
Justin Finger, the league's associate national director.
</TEXT>
