<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     09-18 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Opera, `Rasputin,' Is Startling and Unified</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Rasputin,'' which premiered over the weekend
at the New York City Opera, is a serious and sometimes shockingly
sensual production with a strong sense of unity and easily grasped
plot and music.
   The production, about the power-worshiping ``Mad Monk'' who
advised the family of Russia's last czar, is Jay Reise's first
opera. The 38-year-old Reise, who teaches music at the University
of Pennsylvania, also wrote the libretto.
   Although ``Rasputin'' was sung in English, the libretto was
shown on a screen above the New York State Theater stage so the
audience Saturday night wouldn't have to strain to understand an
unfamiliar opera. Some of the music is tonal, some atonal.
   The opera begins with Rasputin preaching carnal sin as a path to
salvation while a woman in a body stocking writhes on the floor in
front of him. This is more effective than the usual operatic orgy,
in which people wave their arms around sexlessly like undersea
plants moved by waves.
   Bass-baritone John Cheek, who sings with this company and with
the Metropolitan Opera, sang Rasputin. He is tall, young and
well-built for the bare-chested scenes but wasn't quite forceful
enough in his singing or acting.
   Rasputin is such an outrageous character that Cheek could
project still more fire. But he is definitely on the right track.
   Margaret Cusack was Czarina Alexandra, who takes Rasputin's
advice in matters of state because he once stopped her hemophiliac
son's bleeding. Ms. Cusack sung high notes that would cause some
sopranos to screech.
   Price was splendid in the third principal role, Prince Felix
Yusupov. Jon Garrison acted and sang with conviction as a terrified
Czar Nicholas relying on a strong wife. John Lankston also was
splendid as a doctor helpless before hemophilia.
   The staging, by Frank Corsaro, is direct and powerful. A
nightclub scene in which Prince Yusupov sings that he's ``Bebe
d'Amour'' is meant to indicate a decadent society just before it
falls. Price, wearing tailcoat, shorts, nylons, garter belt and
high heels, looks much like Joel Grey in ``Cabaret.''
   There is wonderful use of stylized staging. Erick Avari, in a
nonsinging role as Lenin, gives a speech behind a brightly lighted,
transparent screen. His profile and listeners facing him from
across the stage are silhouetted.
   In another scene, couples dance in silhouette at stage rear,
establishing a ballroom setting and allowing major characters
uncluttered use of the stage front.
   This uncluttered staging looks more German expressionistic than
Russian, but it suits the opera.
   Christopher Keene, who will succeed Beverly Sills as general
director of the company in March, conducted an obviously
well-prepared orchestra.
   The two-act opera isn't unusually long but some of Act 2 might
have been trimmed. Some plot points made crystal clear the first
time are retold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
