<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrailofTears     09-18 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trail of Tears,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Wagons Join ``Trail Of Tears''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small wagon train slowly moved
westward Sunday along the route of the Cherokee Indians' ``Trail of
Tears,'' bolstered by the arrival of two additional wagons and a
bright, blue sky.
   ``A lot of us have stiff muscles and are a little bit saddle
sore but we'll get over that,'' said Ray Morris of Golconda, Ill.,
the coordinator of the wagon train project.
   The wagon train is commemorating the 150th anniversary of the
forced removal of the Cherokees from their eastern homelands to
Oklahoma. About 4,000 of the 13,000 Indians who made the 1,000-mile
march died along the way.
   The six covered wagons set out Saturday from nearby Red Clay
State Historical Park, the last eastern council ground of the
Cherokees, bound for Tahlequah, Okla.
   No Indians have joined the group, but Morris said he expects
several to ride along as the trip progresses.
   Two wagons joined the train Saturday night when the group camped
at a farm just west of Cleveland, 17 miles from the park.
   ``We'll have dozens of wagons joining us, off and on, before we
reach Oklahoma in early December,'' Morris predicted Sunday. He
said the wagon train will average 16 miles a day as it follows the
winding route that the Cherokees took in 1838, when they walked
through Tennessee, Kentucky, Illinois, Missouri, Arkansas and
Oklahoma.
   Two of the more experienced hands on the wagon train are Norman
``Muleman'' Fowler of Camden, Tenn., and his Australian sheep dog,
Clipper.
   ``Me and Clipper are big buddies. We've been on wagon trains
before,'' said Fowler, a mule skinner and logger. A pair of matched
mules pulled his wooden wagon, which is carrying the Tennessee flag
to Oklahoma.
   Fowler said he hoped to make the entire trip to Oklahoma but
might have to stop when the wagon train reaches the Kentucky border
two weeks from now. Fowler said he was expecting financial help
from the state Department of Tourism, but that apparently isn't
going to happen.
   Ricky Todd, the Tennessee state coordinator for the project,
said he is hoping some sponsors will come forward as the wagon
train moves westward.
   ``This is a private, non-profit project,'' said Todd, who raises
and sells horses. ``Our goal is to do some consciousness-raising
about the terrible thing our government did to the Cherokees.
Anybody who wants to help us, or join us, as we travel along the
trail is welcome to do so.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Strat Douthat is the AP Southeast regional
reporter, based in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
