<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Satellite     09-18 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Satellite,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Reportedly Planning Spy Satellite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel was planning to launch an experimental
satellite soon as part of a program to orbit a spy satellite, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   The daily Hadashot, quoting foreign sources, said the
experimental part of the program would last two years and that the
spy satellite is to be carried by Israel's improved Jericho-II
missile.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir refused to confirm or deny the
report.
   ``I don't deal with subjects of this type,'' Shamir said in an
interview with state-run Israel radio. ``You have to turn to the
people and industries that deal with this.''
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres told the radio: ``I can't know
about every subject.'' Defense Ministry spokesman Dan Weinreich and
a Foreign Ministry spokesman declined comment.
   In Washington, the Pentagon and the State Department said they
had no information on the report.
   The newspaper did not further identify its foreign sources used
as a basis for the story. Such attribution is sometimes used by
Israeli newspapers to get around restrictions of the Israeli
military censor.
   Unnamed defense experts were quoted by Hadashot as saying
putting up a spy satellite could increase Israel's deterrence,
providing accurate and immediate information and the investment
would pay for itself by reducing reconnaissance flights.
   The Geneva-based International Defense Review reported in July
that Israel had successfully fired its Jericho missile into the
Mediterranean sea. Its maximum range was to reach 920 miles, the
magazine wrote.
   Two major dailies, Yediot Ahronot and Maariv, devoted front-page
articles Sunday to Israel's reported plan to launch a spy satellite.
   A decision by Israel's 25-member Cabinet, which holds its
regular meetings Sunday, was due on the launching date, Yediot
quoted the British magazine Flight International as saying.
   Yuval Neeman, head of Israel's Space Agency, told The Associated
Press that Israel was in the final stages of developing satellites
for use in communications and science. He said the first Israeli
satellite would probably be launched in 1992 by the European space
consortium Ariane.
   Asked to comment on the reports about a reconnaissance
satellite, Neeman said: ``Our present work is related to scientific
experiments and communications. It doesn't mean that sometime in
the future Israel won't move in such direction (reconnaissance).''
   Last month, Israel announced plans to launch two communication
satellites, Amos-1 and Amos-2, in early 1990s. The satellites are
to be launched by the French Ariane rocket.
   The satellite was the lead item on Israel radio throughout the
day.
</TEXT>
