<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KochBoycott     09-18 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch Boycott,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irish-American Official Calls for `Boycott' of Mayor Koch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINVIEW, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A refusal by New York Mayor Edward I.
Koch to meet with Irish-American leaders led a suburban official to
call Sunday for a sort of boycott of the outspoken mayor.
   Nassau County Comptroller Peter King said at a festival that
Irish-American groups should keep Koch, who is expected to seek
re-election next year, out of their organizations and activities
and resulting photographs.
   King was angered by Koch's refusal Friday to meet with
Irish-American leaders because a member of the Irish Northern Aid
Committee, Martin Galvin, was in the group. The committee supports
the attempt to drive British troops out of Northern Ireland, and
unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mostly Catholic
southern Republic.
   Also in the group Friday was the national president of the
Ancient Order of Hibernians and others who had traveled to New York
City from five states for the scheduled meeting.
   Michael Cummings, spokesman for the national office of the
Ancient Order, disagreed with King's boycott proposal, saying
Irish-Americans should take advantage of contact with Koch to
educate him about the Irish conflict.
   But, he added, ``If I were Mr. Koch, I don't think I would be
attending too many Irish-American functions.''
   Koch has offended people on more than one side of the Irish
conflict, which has resulted in more than 2,000 deaths the past two
decades. When he returned from a trip to Ireland in July, he
suggested the British were a peacekeeping force rather than an
occupying army in Northern Ireland, then backed off and apologized,
angering those who liked his first statement.
   ``It is time to ban him completely from every Irish-American
activity, including the St. Patrick's Day Parade,'' King said.
   Koch, who wears a sweater he bought in Ireland during the parade
and calls himself O'Koch, welcomed the action.
   ``I am happy to be boycotted by Peter King, Mr. Galvin and other
supporters of terrorism,'' Koch said.
   ``So what, I don't care. I consider it a compliment.''
   Koch said that the group had not given him a guest list until
Thursday and when he discovered that Galvin was on it, the mayor
told them he would ``meet with anyone except the representatives of
terrorism.'' The group, he said, declined to reschedule the meeting
without Galvin.
   Pat Murphy, a spokeswoman for King, said that Jack Irwin, state
president of the Ancient Order of Hibernians, supported King's call
for a boycott.
</TEXT>
