<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Yellowstone-FireCommander     09-18 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone-Fire Commander,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Boss Rises To Challenge, But Discouraged By Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto GRDX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denny Bungarz knew he
wanted to be a forest ranger from age 11, when his family camped in
northern California in the 1940s to escape a polio scare.
   He achieved that goal, and 42 years later he ended up being the
fire boss who protected the historic Old Faithful Lodge from the
firestorm that has engulfed Yellowstone National Park, the
country's oldest national park.
   ``Letting that burn would have been an end to everybody's
career, starting with mine,'' said Bungarz, who works in the
Mendocino National Forest in northern California. ``Australia
wouldn't have been far enough away for us.''
   Bungarz, 53, became a local celebrity as he appeared regularly
on national news broadcasts during the wild days of early
September, when the North Fork fire attacked the Old Faithful area
with 400-foot flames.
   That came only several days after the fire roared toward the
Montana community of West Yellowstone on the outskirts of the park.
   Protecting those areas, with the loss of some cabins at Old
Faithful, was one of the few successes of firefighters battling the
335,500-acre blaze.
   Bungarz was the incident commander on the North Fork fire during
those hectic days, but he doesn't consider himself the hero many
people think he is.
   ``We threw everything at that fire from day one. We tried
everything we knew of or could think of,'' he said. But he readily
conceded that in many ways the fire prevailed.
   ``It seemed everything we did didn't work,'' Bungarz said.
``Like one line in camp went, `What does the North Fork fire do
when the wind comes up? Whatever it wants to.'''
   Bungarz said he thinks humor is essential in the tense and often
scary business of fighting fires.
   ``It helps smooth things out when you start to have fun with
each other,'' he said.
   Bungarz directed firefighters on the North Fork fire from a camp
at Madison Junction, 14 miles east of West Yellowstone. He left
over the weekend when his team was relieved.
   Bungarz, like other firefighting officials, knows the political
firestorm over handling of the fires is just beginning. He wouldn't
be surprised to be called to testify before Congress, which plans
hearings on the fires that have affected 1.2 million acres of the
park's 2.2 million acres.
   ``We'll just tell them what happened and what we did,'' Bungarz
said. ``Our work and our meetings have been open (to the public)
all the way and they'll stay that way. If we made mistakes, we'll
take our lumps.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
