<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Priests-GunControl     09-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Priests-Gun Control,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Priests Asked To Support Gun Control Law In Homilies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic priests in the Baltimore
Archdiocese were urged to support the state's handgun control law
during their Sunday homilies to parishioners.
   The request was made by the archdiocese's Justice and Peace
Commission in a strongly worded letter signed by its director,
Christine A.W. Doby.
   A referendum on rescinding the law, which bans cheap, easily
concealable handguns, will be on the Nov. 8 ballot. Opponents
collected enough signatures to bring it before the voters.
   The letter, sent to the 700 priests in the archdiocese, refers
to the opponents of the law as ``apostles of violence'' running ``a
campaign of propaganda based on deception'' in their effort to
defeat the ban.
   There was no immediate indication whether priests had complied
with the request. The archdiocese includes all the state except
southern Maryland, the Washington suburbs and the eastern shore.
   The handgun control law was passed by the 1988 Maryland General
Assembly and signed by Gov. William Donald Schaefer. The law
establishes an appointed board to compile a roster of handguns that
may be made or sold in the state after Jan. 1, 1990.
   Fred Griiser, chairman of the Maryland Committee Against the Gun
Ban, criticized the commission's tactic, saying that by issuing the
letter to priests, the church was ``putting words in the priests'
mouths.''
   ``Does this now mean all Catholics are against us?'' Griiser
asked. ``I don't think what the church is for, is to take a stand
on government issues. I'm sorry to see they're getting involved in
it. If the church's job is spiritual guidance, that's what they
should stick to.''
   Ms. Doby said urging priests to speak on a local public issue
was ``very unusual.'' She said the mailing was ``not the
Archdiocese of Baltimore telling priests: `This is what you're
supposed to say.' These are not marching orders. This is not a
script.''
   The bishops of the Maryland Catholic Conference are already on
record as supporting the law.
   Supporters contend the law will curb the proliferation of cheap
handguns called Saturday Night Specials, while opponents say they
fear it could eventually prohibit the sale of all new handguns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
