<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--ScaffoldingRescue     09-18 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Scaffolding Rescue,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Rescued From 18 Stories Up Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two construction workers were rescued Sunday
evening after spending seven hours trapped on scaffolding dangling
as high as 18 stories up a building, rescue officials said.
   After the motor used to raise and lower the apparatus failed,
Fire Department rescuers and state police lowered ropes with safety
belts to the workers.
   But plans to lower the men, by rope and using a helicopter, were
rejected as too risky. Rescuers finally decided to tell the workers
to disengage the motor and manually lower the scaffolding from the
18th floor.
   The men had lowered themselves by about 7 p.m. to a position
along the First Fidelity Building where fire ladders could reach
them.
   The identity of the two men, who were recaulking the building,
was not immediately available.
</TEXT>
