<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 2255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TheaterShooting     09-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Theater Shooting,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theaters Tighten Security After Two Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two theaters bolstered security after two
youths were shot and hundreds more were involved in fights during
the weekend premiere of a rap music movie.
   The first shooting occurred after the management of a downtown
theater, AMC Midtown, announced the 9:30 showing Friday night of
``Tougher Than Leather'' featuring the rap group Run-DMC was
canceled and asked those with ticket stubs to line up for refunds.
   Fights broke out in the lobby and the auditorium of the theater,
as groups of teen-agers from different neighborhoods taunted each
other and hurled popcorn and soda across the seats, according to
witnesses and police.
   Minutes later, with about 200 people still inside the darkened
auditorium, shots rang out, officials said.
   Filmgoers rushed out of the theater. The injured youth, Wayne
Brown, collapsed a half-block away with a wound in his buttocks.
   Brown was released from Thomas Jefferson University Hospital
Saturday.
   In the second incident, at the Eric 3 on the Campus theater,
near Drexel University and the University of Pennsylvania, two
youths began arguing during the movie at about 10:40 p.m.,
according to usher Charles Hancock.
   ``One guy yells, `I got a gun.' Everybody started rushing for
the doors,'' Hancock said.
   Fights broke out, and before the melee ended, a 19-year-old man
walking by the theater was shot in the hip. Orville Walls was in
good condition Sunday night at the Hospital of the University of
Pennsylvania.
   Police declined to link the shooting with the violence inside
the theater. Walls said Sunday the angle of the shot indicated the
gunman was on the sidewalk and not inside the theater doors.
   Detective Alfred Bilstein said no further incidents were
reported Saturday or Sunday.
   The AMC Midtown canceled two Saturday matinees but reopened
Saturday night with the movie playing on both screens. A half-dozen
police officers stood guard.
   ``We don't feel it is the movie that caused the problems,'' said
Midtown general manager Jim Francisco. ``The movie isn't that
violent. We think the major problem was that we didn't have enough
seats to accommodate all the potential customers.''
   Police agreed.
   ``Now that they are showing in both theaters, they have
alleviated much of the problems,'' Bilstein said. ``No one is
waiting outside now.''
   At the other theater, manager Dean Lindo said he would use seven
security guards instead of two and 10 ushers instead of six.
   ``I'm going to talk with our district manager and try to get
this movie out of here,'' Lindo said. ``We're very upset because
the theater is geared mainly toward college students.''
   Concerts featuring Run-DMC in other cities in recent years have
attracted youth gangs and resulted in violence and relatively large
numbers of drug and theft arrests.
</TEXT>
