<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Pavarotti     09-18 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pavarotti,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pavarotti Sounds Golden at Recital in Met Opera</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Metropolitan Opera started presenting
occasional Sunday recitals by some of its singers in 1978, tenor
Luciano Pavarotti, already a superstar, sang the first one.
   On Sunday, he sang his second one, with Met artistic director
James Levine accompanying on piano. If his voice has lost quality
in the 10 years, you'd never know it from this recital.
   He looks physically fit, too, and has not put back all the
weight he lost in last year's bout of slimming.
   Levine complements a singer beautifully, neither keeping the
piano too far in the background nor pushing too far forward.
   Pavarotti began with a love aria from Mozart's ``Cosi fan
tutte'' and there was a hint of strain there, though a listener had
to strain to be sure of it. From then on, all was golden.
   Pavarotti not only has a surpassingly beautiful tone but it is
individual. If you turn on a radio and he's singing, you know it's
Pavarotti. On Sunday, his voice was flexible in fast passages and
his tones were rounded and substantial. His voice filled out, later
in his career than he expected, from its early small-scaled purity.
   Acting with his voice isn't Pavarotti's strongest quality but he
shaded into an effective pianissimo several times. It wasn't
ultraquiet pianissimo but it was soft enough to express the emotion
called for.
   He bit into the ``M'appari'' aria from Von Flotow's opera
``Martha'' with deep familiarity and the audience responded at the
end with especially lengthy applause.
   Another of the special winners was ``Pourquoi me reveiller''
from Massenet's ``Werther.'' Audiences know how they'd like to hear
that sung in the opera and Pavarotti made that idea materialize. In
the darker parts of the aria, he didn't make it extremely dark,
just shaded.
   He didn't sing only arias but included some art songs, by
Bellini, Respighi and one each by Mascagni, Sibella and Denza.
Encores included an aria from ``Tosca,'' ``Marie Chiare'' by Tosti
and ``Nessun dorma'' from ``Turandot,'' the melodically soaring
aria which Pavarotti likes to make his final encore.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
