<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-VietnamVets     09-18 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Vietnam Vets,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cemetery Dedicated For Canadian Veterans Of Vietnam War</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ST-BERNARD-DE-LACOLLE, Quebec (AP) _ Uniformed veterans marched
in this town near the U.S. border on Sunday and dedicated a
national cemetery for Canadians who fought in the Vietnam War.
   Organizers described the event as the official ``welcome home''
for Canadians who served in the U.S. military in Vietnam.
   The cemetery was named after Richard Paul Dextraze, one of 70
Canadians who died in Vietnam. They were remembered in two days of
religious services and ceremonies in this farming community of
1,500, about 25 miles south of Montreal near the New York border.
   Jacques Dextraze said his family was not surprised when his
younger brother, Richard Paul, went south to join the U.S. Marines.
But he said his father was probably the most upset when the
21-year-old died in action in 1969.
   ``The Canadian government (the military) wasn't doing anything
that excited a kid his age and with the American forces being
involved in Vietnam, he went there for more action,'' said
Dextraze, 45.
   ``It's touching that something has finaly been done for the
fellows in Canada,'' he said. ``It was a long time coming.''
   About 20,000 Canadians served in Vietnam. Currently, the U.S.
government provides some medical benefits for Canadian Vietnam vets.
   Yvon Roy, 44, a burly former member of the U.S. Army's elite
Green Berets, led a platoon of about 30 Canadian Vietnam veterans
in the parade. The procession also included a contingent from the
Royal Canadian Legion, a U.S. Army marching band from Fort Drum,
N.Y., and color guards and a firing squad from Plattsburgh Air
Force Base, N.Y.
   Many of the Vietnam vets wore their service decorations and
camouflaged jungle uniforms.
   About 300 townsfolk lined the half-mile route and applauded the
parade when it procession arrived at the cemetery, where a
miniature replica of the Vietnam War Memorial in Washington is to
be erected Nov. 11.
   The Canadian Forces did not send a delegation. Gen. Paul Manson,
chief of defense staff, told organizers in a letter last week that
Ottawa does not recognize the voluntary participation of Canadians
in foreign conflicts in which Canada does not take part.
   But Roy, one of the event's main organizers, said he was pleased
with the dedication ceremonies, carried out under overcast skies
and which included a 21-gun salute and two U.S. service buglers
blowing taps.
   The only Canadian government representative at the ceremony was
from the Veterans Affairs Department, although Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney sent a message of goodwill, as did President Reagan.
</TEXT>
