<TEXT>
   While many lament the fires that have
charred much of Yellowstone National Park, a wilderness that went
up in smoke just one year ago already displays lush and diverse
greenery that attracts herds of elk.
   ``The fire created more wildlife habitat than anything we could
have ever done,'' Forest Ranger Morris Huffman said of the Deadwood
Summit fire in the Frank Church-River of No Return Wilderness in
the Boise National Forest.
   The fire 250 miles west of Yellowstone burned more than 50,000
acres during the summer of 1987.
   ``It's a natural mosaic now, with open meadows and stands of
timber,'' said forest spokesman Frank Carroll. ``A forest that was
just getting older and deader has now been beautifully revived.''
