<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Japan-Oil     09-18 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Oil,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Stockpiling Oil Despite Gulf Truce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABU DHABI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has increased its
crude oil stockpile despite the cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war and
a world oil glut, a senior Japanese oil executive said Sunday.
   Japan has 170 million barrels of oil stockpiled now and plans to
boost that to 190 million by the end of next March, said Toshikaza
Hashimoto, President of Japan's National Oil Corp.
   Hashimoto, the leader of a Japanese energy delegation touring
the Middle East, said Japan's crude oil demand for the next 10
years would swell to 3.4 million to 3.5 million barrels a day.
   Japan has no oil resources and ranks third among the world's oil
importing countries. Its oil stockpile is enough to meet
consumption for 140 days, Hashimoto disclosed.
   Asked about the need for such a large stockpile, he said: ``The
private sector is required by law to keep such a stockpile.'' He
also cited ``the government's financial situation,'' but did not
elaborate.
   Gulf oil covers 68 percent of Japan's current oil needs,
Hashimoto said.
   Asked if Japan will increase those imports now that a United
Nations-sponsored cease-fire has restored some stability to the
region after eight years of war, he said: ``This depends on supply
and demand.''
   Hashimoto is leading a Japanese energy delegation which also
will visit Oman, Egypt and Saudi Arabia for talks on oil-related
issues.
</TEXT>
