<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-NYUGift     09-18 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYU Gift,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Village Voice Publisher To Give NYU $25 Million Gift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Leonard Stern plans to donate $25
million to New York University, the largest single gift ever made
to the university, Crain's New York Business reported Sunday.
   The money will be used to move the NYU business school from its
current quarters near Wall Street in lower Manhattan to a new
facility at the university's Greenwich Village campus, the business
news magazine stated.
   The graduate business school will be named after Stern, 50, who
earned his undergraduate and graduate degrees in business from New
York University.
   Stern owns the Village Voice and a new newspaper, Manhattan,
which recently expanded from a weekly newspaper to publishing seven
days a week. He is chairman of the Hartz Group, which includes
Hartz Mountain pet products of Secaucus, N.J.
   Crain's said a formal announcement about the donation would be
made after negotiations ``on the scope and function of the gift,
now under discussion, are concluded.''
   Crain's said it would be the largest gift ever made to the
university. A spokesman for the university could not be reached for
comment Sunday.
</TEXT>
