<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Zenith-Brookhurst     09-18 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith-Brookhurst,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Dissidents: We Won't Meet With Company Execs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of dissident shareholders stated Sunday
it would not meet with the Zenith Electronics Corp. board of
directors and repeated a pledge to try to dump directors and sell
the company.
   ``I don't think you need to go in and explain it,'' Peter C.
Harkins of Brookhurst Partners Limited Partnership said of a
meeting with Zenith. ``We've given them a specific proposal to
enhance shareholder value: sell Zenith Electronics Corp.''
   On Friday, Zenith Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman invited Brookhurst
Partners, which has a 6.1 percent stake in Zenith, to a Sept. 26
board meeting, apparently to discuss the dissidents' desire to get
new directors and sell the company.
   But in a letter to Pearlman made public Sunday, Brookhurst
Partners rejected the request for a meeting. The letter said Zenith
had waited too long to improve the company's bottom line, so a sale
makes sense.
   ``It is the responsibility of the board and management to
formulate a plan to enhance Zenith share value,'' the letter says.
``After 3{ years of multimillion-dollar losses, shareowners are
still waiting for the details of your plan.''
   If Zenith does not put iself on the market, Brookhurst Partners
wants other shareholders to vote in favor of trimming the board
from 10 directors to six, retaining three directors and electing
three Brookhurst nominees.
   ``Our nominees will then be pledged to sell the company,''
Harkins, Brookhurst Partners general counsel, said from New York.
   Zenith was closed Sunday and spokesman John Taylor could not be
reached for comment on the letter.
   In order to depose directors, Brookhurst Partners is asking a
federal judge in Delaware to strike a company bylaw that says all
shareholders _ not just a majority _ must favor such a move.
   Based on its 26 million common shares outstanding, and a closing
stock price of $21.75 a share on Friday, Zenith would have a market
value of more than $565 million.
   Brookhurst Partners, formed by Herbert B. Abelow and Nicholas L.
Ihasz, contends the bylaw is illegal. Zenith, a Delaware-chartered
corporation, is based in Glenview, north of Chicago.
   Pearlman has said repeatedly since April that the board was
``exploring all options'' for returning the company to
profitability.
   Zenith, the last remaining U.S. television manufacturer, has
been fighting a losing battle against low-priced imported
televisions.
   Despite the success of its highly regarded computers, Zenith
suffered losses over the past three years, including $19.1 million
last year on sales of $2.36 billion.
   ``We've spoken to major shareholders and they've shared our
views,'' Harkins said of the plan to sell the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
