<FILEID>AP-NR-09-18-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Obit-Thompson     09-18 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Thompson,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fred D. Thompson, Former Times Executive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred D. Thompson, a former vice president of the
New York Times and assistant to the president of the Times Co.,
died of a heart attack while vacationing in Europe. He was 72.
   Thompson, who died Saturday in Fort William, Scotland, was a
Manhattan resident.
   Thompson joined the Times in 1971 after the company bought
Family Circle magazine. He had been president and chief executive
of the magazine since 1969, and remained in those positions until
1975 when he was named the Times' vice president for advertising.
   ``Fred Thompson made a major contribution to the New York Times
during the period in which the Times was being expanded and new
daily sections were being introduced,'' said Walter Mattson,
president of the Times Co.
   In 1979, Thompson was appointed Mattson's assistant, a position
he held until his retirement the following year.
   Earlier in his career, Thompson had held executive positions
with Reader's Digest.
   Thompson was a native of San Antonio, Texas, and moved to New
York with his family when he was 14.
   Survivors include his wife, Julia; four sons; a daughter; and
six grandchildren.
</TEXT>
